      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks. so you mentioned the cold air \"wedging\" itself under the warm air. can u go into more detail on the pressure changes that happen during that process? like how the barometric pressure actually behaves right before and after the front hits?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "As the cold frontal air mass pushes in, surface levels are often occupied by a low-pressure system associated with the warm sector, leading to persistently low or rising barometric pressure right before the front arrives. Once the cold dense air overtakes the front, the newly arriving dry air replaces the low-pressure warm sector, causing the barometric pressure to drop sharply initially and then rapidly fall to its lowest point. Shortly after the front clears, as the cold, stable air mass settles, this low-pressure wave dissipates, and pressure typically begins to drop significantly from its peak to reach a new, low surface pressure equilibrium.",
      "source": "target",
